{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:21:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:21:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1703"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1703"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.05,0.28,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101836"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1703"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3813"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"},{"type":"tags","id":"9102"},{"type":"tags","id":"9118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31301"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101836"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of colicky abdominal pain and abdominal distension. He last opened his bowels five days ago, but is still passing small amounts of flatus. Over the last two months he has experienced increasing constipation with some weight loss. He has a medical history of a splenectomy for trauma at the age of 30 years, hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include atenolol, low dose aspirin and he has recently been started on diclofenac for back pain. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 92/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has a tense, distended abdomen with tinkling bowel sounds. He has a reducible, 8 cm incisional hernia. Digital rectal examination reveals some small faecal pellets. His BMI is 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the distal colon","Sigmoid volvulus","Small bowel adhesive obstruction","Incarcerated incisional hernia","Analgesic-induced constipation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of a large bowel obstruction. The history of increasing constipation over two months with weight loss, followed by acute worsening with abdominal distension and pain, is classic for a gradually narrowing colonic lumen due to malignancy that has now progressed to partial obstruction. \u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the distal colon\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given this presentation, particularly in a 72-year-old man. Left-sided colonic tumours typically present with constipation, narrowing stool calibre, and eventually obstruction as the tumour grows circumferentially around the bowel wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset of severe abdominal pain and absolute constipation (inability to pass flatus or stool). This patient is still passing flatus, which makes volvulus less likely. Additionally, sigmoid volvulus usually presents acutely without the preceding two-month history of worsening constipation and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel adhesive obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration given his history of splenectomy. However, small bowel obstruction typically presents with vomiting early in the course, with abdominal distension developing later. The history of progressive constipation over months points more toward a large bowel process rather than small bowel obstruction, which tends to be more acute in onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncarcerated incisional hernia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as the stem specifically states that the hernia is reducible. An incarcerated hernia would be irreducible and typically causes pain and tenderness at the hernia site. The patient\u0027s symptoms are more generalised and consistent with an intraluminal obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesic-induced constipation\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration as the patient has recently started diclofenac. However, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs like diclofenac are not typically associated with severe constipation (unlike opioids). Furthermore, this would not explain the weight loss or the progressive nature of his symptoms over two months. The combination of weight loss and progressive constipation strongly suggests a malignant process rather than medication-induced constipation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Colorectal cancer commonly presents with a change in bowel habits, weight loss, and abdominal distension.","Left-sided colon cancers typically present with constipation, narrowing of stool calibre, and partial large bowel obstruction.","Recent onset constipation with weight loss in older adults should prompt investigation for colorectal malignancy."],"references":["Catena F, De Simone B, Coccolini F, et al. Bowel obstruction: a narrative review for all physicians. World J Emerg Surg. 2019;14:20. Available at: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-019-0240-7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-04T15:50:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-04T15:54:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101836"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduati